 values), or its squared formula_271 norm (its Euclidean length). Techniques which use an L1 penalty, like LASSO, encourage sparse solutions (where the many parameters are zero). Elastic net regularization uses a penalty term that is a combination of the formula_426 norm and the squared formula_271 norm of the parameter vector.\nHausdorff\u2013Young inequality.\nThe Fourier transform for the real line (or, for periodic functions, see Fourier series), maps formula_503 to formula_504 (or formula_505 to formula_506) respectively, where formula_507 and formula_508 This is a consequence of the Riesz\u2013Thorin interpolation theorem, and is made precise with the Hausdorff\u2013Young inequality.\nBy contrast, if formula_509 the Fourier transform does not map into formula_510\nHilbert spaces.\nHilbert spaces are central to many applications, from quantum mechanics to stochastic calculus. The spaces formula_271 and formula_270 are both Hilbert spaces. In fact, by choosing a Hilbert basis formula_513 i.e., a maximal orthonormal subset of formula_271 or any Hilbert space, one sees that every Hilbert space is isometrically isomorphic to formula_515 (same formula_516 as above), i.e., a Hilbert space of type formula_517\nGeneralizations and extensions.\nWeak \"Lp\".\nLet formula_90 be a measure space, and formula_94 a measurable function with real or complex values on formula_520 The distribution function of formula_94 is defined for formula_522 by\nformula_523\nIf formula_94 is in formula_222 for some formula_8 with formula_527 then by Markov's inequality,\nformula_528\nA function formula_94 is said to be in the space weak formula_222, or formula_531 if there is a constant formula_532 such that, for all formula_533\nformula_534\nThe best constant formula_110 for this inequality is the formula_536-norm of formula_138 and is denoted by\nformula_538\nThe weak formula_11 coincide with the Lorentz spaces formula_540 so this notation is also used to denote them.\nThe formula_536-norm