{"id": "45196", "revid": "12336988", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=45196", "title": "Injective function", "text": "Function that preserves distinctness\nIn mathematics, an injective function (also known as injection, or one-to-one function) is a function \"f\" that maps distinct elements of its domain to distinct elements of its codomain; that is, \"x\"1 \u2260 \"x\"2 implies \"f\"(\"x\"1) \u2260 \"f\"(\"x\"2) (equivalently by contraposition, \"f\"(\"x\"1) \n \"f\"(\"x\"2) implies \"x\"1 = \"x\"2). In other words, every element of the function's codomain is the image of at most one element of its domain. The term one-to-one function must not be confused with one-to-one correspondence that refers to bijective functions, which are functions such that each element in the codomain is an image of \"exactly one\" element in the domain. \nA homomorphism between algebraic structures is a function that is compatible with the operations of the structures. For all common algebraic structures, and, in particular for vector spaces, an injective homomorphism is also called a monomorphism. However, in the more general context of category theory, the definition of a monomorphism differs from that of an injective homomorphism. This is thus a theorem that they are equivalent for algebraic structures; see for more details.\nA function formula_1 that is not injective is sometimes called many-to-one.\nDefinition.\nLet formula_1 be a function whose domain is a set formula_3 The function formula_1 is said to be injective provided that for all formula_5 and formula_6 in formula_7 if formula_8 then formula_9; that is, formula_10 implies formula_11 Equivalently, if formula_12 then formula_13 in the contrapositive statement.\nSymbolically,formula_14\nwhich is logically equivalent to the contrapositive,formula_15An injective function (or, more generally, a monomorphism) is often denoted by using the specialized arrows \u21a3 or \u21aa (for example, formula_16 or formula_17), although some authors specifically reserve \u21aa for an inclusion map. \nExamples.\n\"For visual examples, readers are directed to the gallery section.\"\nMore generally, when formula_18 and formula_38 are both the real line formula_39 then an injective function formula_23 is one whose graph is never intersected by any horizontal line more than once. This principle is referred to as the horizontal line test.\nInjections can be undone.\nFunctions with left inverses are always injections. That is, given formula_41 if there is a function formula_42 such that for every formula_43, formula_44, then formula_1 is injective. The proof is that\nformula_46\nIn this case, formula_28 is called a retraction of formula_48 Conversely, formula_1 is called a section of formula_50\nFor example: formula_51 is retracted by formula_52.\nConversely, every injection formula_1 with a non-empty domain has a left inverse formula_28. It can be defined by choosing an element formula_5 in the domain of formula_1 and setting formula_57 to the unique element of the pre-image formula_58 (if it is non-empty) or to formula_5 (otherwise).\nThe left inverse formula_28 is not necessarily an inverse of formula_61 because the composition in the other order, formula_62 may differ from the identity on formula_63 In other words, an injective function can be \"reversed\" by a left inverse, but is not necessarily invertible, which requires that the function is bijective.\nInjections may be made invertible.\nIn fact, to turn an injective function formula_64 into a bijective (hence invertible) function, it suffices to replace its codomain formula_38 by its actual image formula_66 That is, let formula_67 such that formula_68 for all formula_43; then formula_28 is bijective. Indeed, formula_1 can be factored as formula_72 where formula_73 is the inclusion function from formula_74 into formula_63\nMore generally, injective partial functions are called partial bijections.\nProving that functions are injective.\nA proo